    <section id="what-is" class="content-section">
      <h2>What is Hyperthyroidism?</h2>
      <p>Hyperthyroidism occurs when the thyroid gland produces too much thyroid hormone, accelerating the body's metabolism. It is one of the most common conditions in older cats — typically diagnosed in cats over 10 years old.</p>
      <p>Three of our cats had hyperthyroidism: Artie, who had planned radioactive iodine treatment before his decline made that impossible; Murphy, who had a brief hyperthyroid period before her cancer diagnosis; and Sorbet, who is currently managed for it.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="ckd-overlap" class="content-section">
      <h2>The CKD Overlap — The Thing Vets Don't Always Explain</h2>
      <p>Hyperthyroidism and CKD frequently occur together in senior cats — and treating the thyroid can "unmask" hidden kidney disease. This is one of the most important things to understand about managing both conditions.</p>
      <p>An overactive thyroid artificially increases blood flow to the kidneys, which can make kidney function appear better than it actually is. When you treat the hyperthyroidism and thyroid hormone drops, kidney function markers (creatinine, BUN) often rise — sometimes significantly.</p>
      <div class="content-callout content-callout--amber">
        <strong>Before committing to permanent treatment</strong> (radioactive iodine or surgery), many specialists recommend a trial of medication first — to see how kidney values respond when thyroid hormone is controlled. If kidney function drops significantly on the trial, the treatment plan may need to change. Ask your vet about this specifically.
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="treatment" class="content-section">
      <h2>Treatment Options</h2>
      <div class="meds-list">
        <div class="med-item">
          <div class="med-name">Methimazole (Tapazole / Felimazole)</div>
          <div class="med-desc">The most common first-line treatment. Available as a tablet or transdermal ear gel. Controls thyroid hormone but does not cure the condition — requires ongoing daily administration. Used as a trial before permanent treatment, or as long-term management when other options aren't suitable. Available in the US and Canada.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="med-item">
          <div class="med-name">Radioactive Iodine (I-131)</div>
          <div class="med-desc">The gold-standard curative treatment. A single injection of radioactive iodine destroys the abnormal thyroid tissue permanently. Very high success rate. Requires a short period of isolation post-treatment due to radioactivity. Not available at all vet clinics — requires a specialist centre. Artie had this planned before his decline made it impossible.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="med-item">
          <div class="med-name">Thyroidectomy (surgery)</div>
          <div class="med-desc">Surgical removal of the affected thyroid tissue. Curative in most cases. Less commonly chosen than radioactive iodine, but an option when I-131 isn't accessible or appropriate.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="med-item">
          <div class="med-name">Hill's y/d prescription diet</div>
          <div class="med-desc">An iodine-restricted diet that can control hyperthyroidism when it is the only food the cat eats. Difficult to maintain if the cat has access to other food or treats. Limited usefulness in multi-cat households.</div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="vet-questions" class="content-section">
      <h2>Questions to Ask Your Vet</h2>
      <ul class="vet-questions">
        <li>Should we do a methimazole trial before committing to radioactive iodine, to see how kidney values respond?</li>
        <li>What is my cat's T4 level, and what is our target range on treatment?</li>
        <li>Is my cat's kidney disease being masked by the hyperthyroidism?</li>
        <li>Is radioactive iodine available in our area, and is my cat a candidate?</li>
        <li>If we use methimazole long-term, what monitoring does that require?</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

